ire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Foliot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Lombardy): variant of   Foglio  . This surname is very rare in Italy."],"variants":[{"name":"Foglio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Dino, Flavio, Julieta, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: probably from the Latin personal name <i>Folius</i> (which is embodied in the common placename Fogliano)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Foliot was born in 1276, in Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir William Foliot, was 22 and his mother, Audrey Falco, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Sibil de Thornden."},"et":{"1276–":"1276–Surnud","1276–Male":"1276–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","Abt. 1295":"umbes 1295","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornden, Windmill, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1276–":"1276–Kuollut","1276–Male":"1276–Kuollut","1272–Female":"1272–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","Abt. 1295":"noin 1295","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Thornden, Windmill, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1276–":"1276–Décédé","1276–Male":"1276–Décédé","1272–Female":"1272–Décédée","1295–Male":"1295–Décédé","1255–1312":"1255–1312","1245–Female":"1245–Décédée","1312":"1312","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1276":"1276","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","Abt. 1295":"environ 1295","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Thornden, Windmill, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Foliot est né en 1276, à Worcester, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Sir William Foliot, avait 22 ans et sa mère, Audrey Falco, avait 32 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sibil de Thornden."},"de":{"1276–":"1276–Verstorben","1276–Male":"1276–Verstorben","1272